postcontent:
Up for sale is a 1928 Finnish M27 Mosin Nagant. This gun is in very good condition for its age, and is highly collectible. 

The serial numbers on the rifle are considered to be a Finn Match meaning that the serial numbers on the barrel and bolt are matching but the other numbers do not match. This is very common in Finnish Mosin Nagants. 

I am asking $375 for the rifle and 440 rounds of ammo. Or I will sell just the rifle for $325. Prices are somewhat negotiable, but please note that these rifles can sell for quite a bit more than I am asking. Thanks and Happy Holidays.

History:
The 10-year Federal Assault Weapons Ban (AWB) was passed by the U.S. Congress on September 13, 1994, and was signed into law by President Bill Clinton the same day. Ruger still made the Mini-14 magazines in 20 rounds, but during those years, they had to have the stamp, "RESTRICTED LAW ENFORCEMENT / GOVERNMENT USE ONLY" to indicated they were restricted to civilians. title: For Sale/Trade:  1940's Nazi Marked Browning Hi-Power 9mm P-35 German Occupation Army WWII
postcontent:
DESCRIPTION: This is a very beautiful old Belgium made Browning produced during Nazi control. It is a German Occupational Army pistol with matching serial numbers on the frame, slide and barrel. Both also have the Nazi Eagle over Swastika proof marks and designation of AaW140. A great piece of history with matching serial numbers. I have shot this pistol and it shoots like a dream. What a conversation piece!



BROWNING HISTORIAN: After contacting Glen, the Browning historian it was determined this exact pistol was produced for the German Occupational Army between 1940-1944. By the serial number the best info we can determine this was made approximately in 1941. With limited records, it is difficult to determine the exact date. If this pistol could talk I bet it would have some great stories to tell!



PROOF MARKINGS: The frame is marked with the German Eagle over swastika, the WaA140 acceptance mark, the front left side of the trigger guard is marked “H” and the right side has the serial number “168294”. The barrel is marked with an “Eagle” and “168294”. The bottom of the frame next to the magazine well is marked “L” and what appears to be a C inside of a circle. These are difficult to see, however if they are important, please request more details and we can try to view it with a jewelers loops.



SERIAL AND DATING: Belgium Browning manufactured approximately in 1941, a very low serial number. The “168294” serial number is the lowest serial number I have viewed on Gunbroker or anywhere else!



GRIPS: These appear to the be correct walnut grips in good condition for their age. Checkering still present and in good condition.



BARREL: Approximately 4 3/4" barrel with good bore and rifling.



ACTION: Very smooth and crisp action. This was test fired and worked well for me.



MAGAZINE: These appears to be a very old magazine. Not certain if this is the original magazine but I can take more pic if this is important to know.



HISTORY: FN commissioned John Browning to design a new military sidearm conforming to this specification. Browning had previously sold the rights to his successful M1911 U.S. Army automatic pistol to Colt's Patent Firearms, and was therefore forced to design an entirely new pistol while working around the M1911 patents. Browning built two different prototypes for the project in Utah and filed the patent for this pistol in the United States on June 28, 1923 and granted on February 22, 1927.[5][6] One was a simple blowback design, while the other was operated with a locked-breech recoil system. Both prototypes utilized the new staggered magazine design (by designer Dieudonné Saive) to increase capacity without unduly increasing the pistol's grip size or magazine length. By 1931, the Hi-Power design incorporated a shortened 13-round magazine, a curved rear grip strap, and a barrel bushing that was integral to the slide assembly. By 1934, the Hi-Power design was complete and ready to be produced. It was first adopted by Belgium for military.
